        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Rl College of Surgeons | London</placeName>
                    <date>20 September 1854</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                  <p>I lose no time in informing you that the tooth, which I received, with your note of the 1 <hi rend="superscript">st</hi> Sep. <hi rend="superscript">t</hi>, this morning, is, as your inscription rightly states, the upper molar tooth of an Ox, i.e., of a species of the genus Bos; it is of a young animal, and, owing to its incomplete state of formation, I have not been able, after much comparison, to determine satisfactorily whether it belongs to a large variety of the common Ox, or whether to a female of the Bos primigenius, or Bison-priscus.</p>
                  <p>I am sorry I cannot satisfy you &amp; myself on this point, but I am always happy to do my best for kind &amp; zealous fellow-investigators of Nature, like yourself. No apology is ever needed, in such cases, by</p>
                  <p>your’s most truly |Richard Owen</p>
                  <p>[P.S.] The tooth will be safely delivered when I see you early in November. R.O.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
        
